article.headline: Alabama 77, Vanderbilt 74 (OT)
article.story: TUSCALOOSA, Ala. (AP) -- Ronald Steele hit two free throws with 9.7 seconds left in overtime and scored 21 points to lead Alabama to a 77-74 victory over Vanderbilt on Wednesday night. The Crimson Tide (13-8, 6-3 Southeastern Conference) survived a dramatic finish to regulation that featured eight points in the final 8 seconds. Alex Gordon cut it to 75-74 on two free throws with 47 seconds left in overtime for Vanderbilt (12-8, 3-6), which has lost four in a row. At the other end, Jean Felix missed a 3 but Richard Hendrix dove for the rebound and called timeout with 12 seconds to play. Steele grabbed the inbounds pass and drew the foul, draining both free throws. Shan Foster, who finished with 30 points and had six second-half 3-pointers, drew a foul with 2.3 seconds left and missed his first free throw. Derrick Byars rebounded and passed to Dan Cage, who missed a 3 at the buzzer. Steele has iced back-to-back games at the line, also making six straight in the final two minutes of a win over LSU on Saturday. It could hardly match the frenetic ending to regulation. Felix had missed his first eight 3-point attempts but drilled one with eight seconds left for a 66-65 lead. Then Foster hit an open 3 with 2.3 seconds to play. Felix launched an inbounds pass the length of the court to Hendrix, who bounced it inside to Gee for a dunk that just beat the buzzer. Davidson had 21 points and 10 rebounds for the Tide. Alonzo Gee scored 17 off the bench while Hendrix had 12 rebounds to go with eight points. Felix finished 1-for-14 and missed 10 of 11 3s. Foster made 6-of-13 3s after missing his only two attempts in the first half. Byars finished with 13 points, while the Commodores set up 21 of their 28 baskets with assists. They were 9-of-15 on 3s in the second half. The Commodores were playing their first game without senior guard Mario Moore, who took a temporary leave of absence a day earlier for medical reasons. Vandy's bread-and-butter 3s didn't fall in OT. The Commodores made their first and then missed their last three. The Commodores had won the last four meetings. Steele fared well in his game against former high school teammate DeMarre Carroll, who finished with nine points and nine boards. Carroll and Julian Terrell both fouled out in overtime.
